pull_request.title: Fix multiplayer join logic - add auto-start for 2+ players
pull_request.body:
## Problem

When 2 or more players join the server, nothing happens - no lobby sync, player spawn, or level start. Players would remain stuck in the lobby indefinitely with no game progression, making multiplayer functionality effectively broken.

## Root Cause

The server only had auto-start logic for single players via `CheckAndHandleSinglePlayerAutoStart()`. When multiple players joined, the server would:
- Successfully accept both connections 
- Send initial client data and lobby state
- But never transition from lobby to a game map
- Leave players waiting indefinitely

## Solution

Added comprehensive multiplayer auto-start functionality:

### New Configuration Options
- `AutoStartMultiplayer` (bool, default: true) - Whether to automatically start games when minimum players join
- `MinPlayersForAutoStart` (int, default: 2) - Minimum number of players required to auto-start a multiplayer game

### Server Logic Changes
- Replaced `CheckAndHandleSinglePlayerAutoStart()` with `CheckAndHandleAutoStart()` 
- Added `StartGameForPlayers()` method to handle map transitions for any number of players
- Server now detects when player count reaches the minimum threshold and automatically starts the game

### Command Line Support
```bash
# Enable/disable multiplayer auto-start
--auto_start_multiplayer true/false

# Set minimum players (2-10)
--min_players_for_auto_start 3
```

### Configuration File Support
```json
{
  "AutoStartMultiplayer": true,
  "MinPlayersForAutoStart": 2
}
```

## Testing

The fix has been validated with:
- Successful builds with no errors
- Server startup verification with new configuration options
- Command line argument validation (rejects invalid values)
- Configuration file loading with new properties

## Backward Compatibility

‚úÖ Fully backward compatible - existing single-player auto-start functionality is preserved
‚úÖ Default settings maintain current behavior for single players
‚úÖ Existing configuration files work without modification

## Expected Behavior After Fix

1. **Player 1 joins** ‚Üí Connects to lobby normally
2. **Player 2 joins** ‚Üí Server detects 2 players ‚â• MinPlayersForAutoStart
3. **Auto-start triggers** ‚Üí Server calls `StartGameForPlayers("Multiplayer auto-start with 2 players")`
4. **Map transition** ‚Üí Server sends MapChange packets to all clients  
5. **Game begins** ‚Üí Both players are now in a game map and can play together

Server logs will show:
```
Auto start multiplayer set to: True
Minimum players for auto start set to: 2
Multiplayer auto-start with 2 players: Transitioning to map X (Type: Y)
```

This fixes the core multiplayer experience by ensuring games actually start when players join, rather than leaving them stranded in the lobby.

issue.title: [WIP] Detailed Plan: C++ Implementation of SVM/Solana Validator
issue.body:
Thanks for assigning this issue to me. I'm starting to work on it and will keep this PR's description up to date as I form a plan and make progress.

Original issue description:

> ## Objective
> Develop a native C++ implementation for a Solana validator, integrating SVM (Solana Virtual Machine) logic for performance and low-level blockchain interaction. This empowers the repository to participate as a full validator node, contributing to consensus, block validation, and staking operations directly from C++.
> 
> ## Expanded Plan
> 
> ### 1. Requirements Analysis
> - Study Solana validator requirements and SVM architecture.
> - Review Solana core protocols (gossip, consensus, ledger, voting, staking).
> - Identify dependencies: cryptography, networking, serialization, SVM execution engine.
> - Analyze resource and performance constraints for C++ (memory, concurrency, async I/O).
> 
> ### 2. Design Architecture
> - Define modular components:
>   - Network Layer (gossip, RPC, cluster communication)
>   - Ledger Management (block storage, transaction history)
>   - Validator Core (block validation, vote production, fork choice)
>   - Staking and Rewards (stake management, reward distribution)
>   - SVM Execution Engine (program loading, execution, state transitions)
> - Specify interfaces between components; design for testability.
> - Plan for configuration, logging, and error handling.
> 
> ### 3. Implementation Plan
> #### a. Network Layer
> - Integrate gossip protocol for peer discovery and cluster updates.
> - Implement RPC endpoints for validator interaction.
> - Ensure secure and efficient message passing (consider TLS, DoS resistance).
> 
> #### b. Ledger Management
> - Design append-only data structures for block/transaction storage.
> - Implement serialization/deserialization for Solana block format.
> - Validate block integrity and chain consistency.
> 
> #### c. Validator Core
> - Implement block validation rules per Solana consensus.
> - Implement voting logic and fork choice algorithm.
> - Integrate with cluster to submit votes and respond to forks.
> 
> #### d. Staking and Rewards
> - Implement stake account handling, delegation, and reward calculation.
> - Ensure compatibility with Solana‚Äôs staking model.
> 
> #### e. SVM Execution Engine
> - Integrate or implement SVM for program execution.
> - Handle program loading, state transitions, and error cases.
> - Optimize execution for performance and security.
> 
> ### 4. Testing and Validation
> - Unit and integration tests for all components.
> - Performance and stress-testing under realistic validator scenarios.
> - Test compatibility with Solana testnet/devnet.
> 
> ### 5. Documentation
> - Detail architecture, configuration, and deployment steps.
> - Provide usage examples and troubleshooting guide.
> 
> ### 6. Milestones
> - [ ] Initial architecture & requirement analysis
> - [ ] Network layer prototype
> - [ ] Ledger management prototype
> - [ ] Validator core with basic validation
> - [ ] Staking & rewards
> - [ ] SVM integration
> - [ ] Full validator testnet participation
> - [ ] Documentation and examples
> 
> ## Acceptance Criteria
> - Fully operational C++ Solana validator node
> - Passes all provided test cases and testnet integration
> - Modular, well-documented, and performant
> - Code reviewed and aligned with project‚Äôs contribution standards
> 
> ---
> This plan is comprehensive and actionable. Shall I proceed with breaking down into implementation issues or specific tasks?
>

This can be done with language-specific fonts, but modern fonts often support all options and use the lang tag. Han unification: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Han_unification Related issue for Chrome client-side canvas: https://github.com/mapbox/tiny-sdf/pull/58 I'm submitting the code and test as a draft PR because **this is still failing** to change the output. I did rebuild bindings, and tried with and without `pango_cairo_update_layout`. Other ideas: this is failing to set the language, setting it at the wrong time, the fonts or something needs to be reset, or pango handles Han unification using something else? I'm a longtime node-canvas user but new to the internals. I found this reference to `PANGO_LANGUAGE` and `%PANGO_SCRIPT_HAN` https://github.com/gtk-rs/gir-files/blob/main/Pango-1.0.gir#L11631

pull_request.title: [WIP] Detailed Plan: C++ Implementation of SVM/Solana Validator
pull_request.body:
Thanks for assigning this issue to me. I'm starting to work on it and will keep this PR's description up to date as I form a plan and make progress.

Original issue description:

> ## Objective
> Develop a native C++ implementation for a Solana validator, integrating SVM (Solana Virtual Machine) logic for performance and low-level blockchain interaction. This empowers the repository to participate as a full validator node, contributing to consensus, block validation, and staking operations directly from C++.
> 
> ## Expanded Plan
> 
> ### 1. Requirements Analysis
> - Study Solana validator requirements and SVM architecture.
> - Review Solana core protocols (gossip, consensus, ledger, voting, staking).
> - Identify dependencies: cryptography, networking, serialization, SVM execution engine.
> - Analyze resource and performance constraints for C++ (memory, concurrency, async I/O).
> 
> ### 2. Design Architecture
> - Define modular components:
>   - Network Layer (gossip, RPC, cluster communication)
>   - Ledger Management (block storage, transaction history)
>   - Validator Core (block validation, vote production, fork choice)
>   - Staking and Rewards (stake management, reward distribution)

## Pull Request Overview

This PR addresses critical CI build failures in the LaTeX workflow by correcting GitHub Actions configuration and adding missing LaTeX packages. The changes fix both syntax errors in YAML files and package installation issues that were preventing successful PDF generation.

### Key changes:
- Fixed YAML syntax by properly quoting the 'on' keyword in workflow files
- Updated dante-ev/latex-action from v2.0.0 to @latest with correct latexmk arguments
- Added comprehensive LaTeX package installation including German language support and fontawesome5
